b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe46074.htm)  [Next](sbe46076.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0543983846/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_Vedic Hymns, Part II (SBE46)_ , by Hermann Oldenberg [1897], at sacred-\ntexts.com\n\n* * *\n\np. 271\n\n### MA _N_ _D_ ALA III, HYMN 15.\n\n#### ASH _T_ AKA III, ADHY\xc3\x82YA 1, VARGA 15.\n\n1\\. Flaming with thy broad stream of light beat away fiends, sorcerers,\nplagues. May I dwell in the protection of the great, well-protecting (god),\nunder the guidance of Agni who readily listens to our call.\n\n2\\. Be thou our protector when this dawn shines forth, he thou (our protector)\nwhen the sun has risen. Cherish, O Agni, well-born in body, this praise of\nmine as (a man rejoices) in the birth (of a son), in his own offspring\n[1](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:2:1).\n\n3\\. Beholding men, shine thou after many (dawns)\n[1](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:3:1), O bull, Agni, red in the dark (nights). O Vasu!\nLead us and bring us across anguish. Help us, the U _s_ i _g_ s\n[2](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:3:2), to wealth [3](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:3:3), thou\nyoungest (of the gods)!\n\n4\\. Shine, O Agni, thou the invincible bull, who hast conquered all\nstrongholds and all delights, the leader of the first, the protecting\n[1](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:4:1), mighty sacrifice, O _G_ atavedas, best guide.\n\n5\\. O singer, thou who art wise, brightly shining towards the gods\n[1](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:5:1), bring to us thy many perfect shelters, and gain\nlike a victorious car [2](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:5:2); Agni, (carry) thou\n(hither) towards us the two well-established [3](sbe46075.htm#an_3:15:5:3)\nworlds (Heaven and Earth).\n\n6\\. O bull, increase and rouse our gains. Agni! (Increase) for us the two\nworlds (Heaven and Earth) rich in milk, O god together with the gods, shining\nwith beautiful shine! May a mortal's hatred never enclose us.\n\n7 = III, 1, 23.\n\np. 272\n\n#### NOTES.\n\nThe _Ri_ shi is Utkila Katya, the metre Trish _t_ ubh.--Verse 1 = VS. XI, 49;\nTS. IV, 1, 5, 1; MS. II, 7, 5; III, 1, 6.\n\n##### Verse 2\n\nNote 1. Comp. VII, 1, 21. tanaye nitye; X, 39, 14. nityam na sunum tanayam\ndadhana _h_ , and besides II, 26, 3. _g_ anena \xe2\x80\xa6 vi _s_ a\xc2\xb4 \xe2\x80\xa6 _g_ anmana \xe2\x80\xa6\nputrai _h_ ; Hirzel, Gleichnisse und Metaphern im Rig-veda, 77.\n\n##### Verse 3.\n\nNote 1. For this expression, compare IV, 19, 8; IX, 71, 7; X, 31, 7, and\nespecially III, 6, 7; VI, 39, 4.\n\nNote 2. The poet compares himself and his friends with the mythical priestly\ntribe of the U _s_ i _g_ s (Bergaigne, Religion Vedique, I, 57 seq.), using,\nas it seems, at the same time the word u _s_ i _g_ a _h_ in its adjective\nsense 'the willing ones.'\n\nNote 3. The Padapa\xc2\xb4 _th_ a is right in giving raye; comp. VIII, 26, 13. _s_\nubhe _k_ akrate.\n\n##### Verse 4.\n\nNote 1. Is the text correct? I think that payo _h_ should be corrected into\npayo or payu _h_ : 'the leader and protector of the first mighty sacrifice.'\nThe mistake may have been caused by the genitives which surround the word.\n\n##### Verse 5.\n\nNote 1. Geldner (Vedische Studien, I, 160) translates this hemistich: 'Die\nvielen sicheren Zufluchtsorte (= Opferplatze) bis zu den Gottern erleuchtend\nals Weiser, o Sanger.' I do not believe that _s_ arma is the object of\ndi\xc2\xb4dyana _h_ ; and 'Zufluchtsorte = Opferplatze' is too much in the style of\nSaya _n_ a. I take a _k_ _kh_ idra _s_ arma as depending on abhi vakshi; comp.\nI, 34, 6. tridha\xc2\xb4tu _s_ arma vahatam.\n\nNote 2. For abhi vakshi va\xc2\xb4 _g_ am, comp. III, 30, 11; VI, 21, 12.\n\nNote 3. On sumeka, comp. Windisch, Festgruss an Boehtlingk, 114.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: III, 16](sbe46076.htm)\n\n"